Linux Essentials

Right now, I’m studying for the Linux Essentials certification from the Linux Professional Institute (LPI). This course is designed to teach the foundations of Linux and help students pass the certification exam on the first attempt. As someone working toward a career in IT and cybersecurity, learning Linux is an important step for me.

Linux is an open-source operating system based on an older system called Unix. Unlike Windows or macOS, there is no single company that owns Linux. Instead, Linux was started by Linus Torvalds, and it has grown with the help of thousands of developers around the world.

One of the things that makes Linux unique is that anyone can see and modify the source code. Because of this, many different versions of Linux exist. These versions are called distributions, such as Ubuntu, Fedora, and Debian. Each distribution may look different, but they all share the same Linux core.

Another interesting thing I learned is just how widely Linux is used. In fact, most of the internet runs on Linux. Over 96% of the top web servers in the world use Linux as their operating system. That means when we browse websites or watch videos online, we are often interacting with Linux systems behind the scenes.

Linux is not only used for servers. It is also used for desktop computers, smartphones, and many smart devices. For example, Android phones are actually based on Linux. Many smart home devices, security cameras, and even smart TVs also run Linux.

In this course, I will learn the history of Linux, basic commands, security concepts, and system administration skills. There will also be hands-on labs and activities to practice using the Linux command line. This is important because working in IT often requires being comfortable using the terminal.

Learning Linux may feel challenging at first, but it is a powerful skill. It opens the door to careers in system administration, cloud computing, cybersecurity, and networking.

For me, this is just the beginning of my Linux journey, and I’m excited to continue learning more.
